The.first week of the project was spent working out the tasks that we will need to.accomplish in our project.
I started to.read about Particle, since the Internet of Things is at the heart of this.project.
Particle makes hardware devices.and trackers, and software, and has an IDE, and command-line interface and a.  coding workspace called Workbench.
In.the second week, I planned to read all the documentation.
This did not happen, but will have to happen.first thing this week.

To.begin the project, I also read about RabbitMQ, since message queuing at protocols is also a key process, but one that I have not had experience with â€“.either coding or envisioning â€“ in any of my courses.
This coming week I will read everything that I can find about RabbitMQ.
Discussions.with Toto and Gogo helped to clarify how the sensor devices link to the cloud.and how the data are sent to Winely.
Toto could picture it immediately and drafted a second version of the.UML diagram.
I had been looking to map.the project with such a diagram since the first studio project when it was not.clear when decisions would be made and by whom.
We now need to make a work process flow diagram with Toto and Gogo to.indicate what code we are each writing and where group decisions should be.made.
The Agile process gives us a way.to split the projects vertically so that all 3 team members are involved in.each user story.
We will have our first.scrum this coming week (Week 3).

As.Team Communicator for Studio Project 2, I set up our Teams meetings daily and.also made a follow-up meeting with the client to ask them about their priorities.among the few user stories we developed in Teacher3â€™s Agile workshop.
I recorded and transcribed the meeting,.because Gogo had been unable to make it and I wanted him to be able to read the.transcripts and listen to the audio.
I.  scanned the sheets we used in Teacher3â€™s workshop and added them to the files on.our Teams site.
To follow up this coming.week, we will need to examine each specific user story to see exactly what is.needed.
During this.past week, the second week, I wanted to contribute more actively to finding ways to send the.email to our client, which is our first user story.

I found that we can do this in R Zuzudown by.writing a document with the code embedded to display a table and any related.visualisations (which we are not sure that we need right now) that are to be.sent to the client only when a device is down.
I now have a code chunk in RStudio to use that will do this and need to work on the.if { } else { } statement to set the conditions for when to send the email.
We.should be able to do this by 28 July, our first date to deliver part of our.solution to Winely.
To.improve this week, I will spend more time learning the languages we will be.using, such as JavaScript in node.js.
I will find it most challenging to learn how.to write API requests and fetch responses, how to recognise webhooks and how to.poll the devices at regular intervals.
